ğŸ”·Exploring Rest Parameters in JavaScriptğŸ”·

Rest parameters allows us to represent an indefinite number of arguments as an array. This can be incredibly useful when writing functions that need to handle varying numbers of inputs.

ğŸ”·Key Points ğŸ”·
ğŸ”¹ Flexibility: Rest parameters allows us to handle functions with an unknown number of arguments.
ğŸ”¹Array Methods: Since rest parameters are an array, we can use array methods like map, filter, and reduce on them.
ğŸ”¹Order: Rest parameters must be the last parameter in the function definition. we canâ€™t have any parameters after the rest parameter.

ğŸ”·Syntax ğŸ”· 
The rest parameter syntax uses three dots ... followed by the name of the array that will contain the rest of the arguments.

 function exampleFunction(...args) 
 {
 console.log(args);
 }
 exampleFunction(1, 2, 3, 5, 8,10);
 // Output: [1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 10]

Rest parameters are a powerful feature in JavaScript that enhance the flexibility and readability of our code. They allow us to easily manage functions with an unknown number of arguments, making our code cleaner and more efficient. 

Next time you're handling multiple parameters, give rest parameters a try!
